_owuv0k2ZzQV9aynOXX0-3wvIROsPY57rnhMcI2fkF4oWHV0sf4HGGDK23F0eHvRvGmdFaKa7Uh=
dP5BadGaCpJT46lu_J_6B_IDYFe] put it succinctly: =E2=80=9CThe profitability =
of order flow determines its pricing power. The product is the user, and hi=
gh volume of non-toxic (uninformed) order flow in high spread options trade=
s is highly profitable.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Saying Robinhood traders are unsophisticated isn=E2=80=99t mean; it=E2=80=
=99s facts. The market puts a price on how bad the trading on each platform=
 is, and it pays Robinhood more than anyone else.=C2=A0
The fact is, value judgments aside, the company is clearly incentivized to =
get people to trade more often, to trade more options, and to trade on marg=
in. The ideal trader on Robinhood, from a revenue perspective, is a Robinho=
od Gold subscriber who frequently trades options on margin. That also happe=
ns to be the riskiest kind of trading behavior for the individual traders t=
hemselves.
When things go wrong, which they inevitably do, and someone criticizes Robi=
nhood, the company hides behind the guise of democratizing access to the ma=
rkets, saying something like:=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a free market! They=E2=80=99re adults! Are you saying they are=
n=E2=80=99t entitled to the same wealth creation opportunities as the big f=
ancy hedge funds just because they weren=E2=80=99t born rich? We=E2=80=99re=
 on the side of the little guy! Whose side are YOU on anyway? Elite=E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0
This is Silicon Valley 101. It feels wrong, using slick and disingenuous ma=
rketing to obscure misaligned incentives, but all of the big tech companies=
 do some version of this. As long as it operates within the legal and regul=
atory bounds, though, Robinhood is able, and even fiduciarily obligated, to=
 do whatever it takes to maximize shareholder value.=C2=A0
But, as last week showed, Robinhood is also subject to the savagery of the =
market. It can=E2=80=99t externalize all of the real risk it generates with=
 words alone.=C2=A0
Robinhood, WSB, and Entropy Theory=C2=A0
In 2013, two Stanford grads, Baiju Bhatt and Vlad Tenev, founded Robinhood,=
 based, so the story [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOgzAM_JrmiJKQ=
AD3ksJf-BsrDhah5KRi6_P2m5bCWZVu2xqMZqxGWXE9V8obkU2Y8C6gE7y0AIlSyb1Bn7xQb-NR=
LcSdOCccmORG_zc8KELUPCusOpOwmeKvR5_RFUMolWdXdiaeV91GMBvQg-WC1dOMgR9FTY6S4eP=
XuPCQLCg6oZ05AgloRy3brf2780RJXwDckPKNPO8JhO5tj2x9BO4QER5uJV5xyRjllrJctOtZFU=
34LVFF6exM0LrzbdrOhtq_PA1JVymhy9Wlp59eqI4TvocmZW4978njOkLQJ4C6leBn21T4vjbs2=
I92ssdnEOJvGUUou5aWsWdFzOvUjFaQxu9xQ6Z_0DwOWhLk] goes, on two simultaneous =
events: Occupy Wall Street and the rise of mobile. They set out to build a =
mobile commission-free trading app that =E2=80=9Cuntethered the financial m=
arkets from the typical computer setup with multiple monitors.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
Between 2013 and 2017, Robinhood was a typical Silicon Valley startup. It u=
sed technology to make trading easy, and introduced innovations like commis=
sion-free trading and fractional shares, which genuinely democratized acces=
s to investing.=C2=A0
Source: Crunchbase
By 2017, Robinhood had raised a little under $70 million. In April 2017, it=
 became a unicorn when it raised a $110 million Series C at a $1.3 billion =
valuation from DST after crossing the 2 million mark and growing its Robinh=
ood Gold Subscription product. Between the C and D, Robinhood introduced tw=
o products that would help fuel its growth - commissions-free options and c=
rypto trading. In December 2017, when they rolled out options, I predicted =
how this was going to end.=C2=A0
In May 2018, it raised a $363 million Series D [https://email.mg2.substack.=
com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQhU_T7DSA0o0LFrOZaxh-SiUqECi7x9sPo4upkCKVyst79VmNMMd8qhQLk=
r824plABfiUDRAhk6NAHr1T7MllJ_qBONU7JoUkvoxTBti13xTmA0g6zOatRh_DpaCUC7IoKZzr=
