yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;">There was also a meme, less cartoon and more condescension, among more =
serious markets types about what would happen to Robinhood traders when the=
y got too long on margin and the market finally turned against them. They&#=
8217;d Robinhood themselves into financial ruin.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Robinhoo=
d, this idea went, made it too easy for unsophisticated investors to trade =
on margin (borrow money to buy stocks or options). That works really well w=
hen stocks go up, and really poorly when they go down.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">If=
 you own a bunch of stocks on margin, and the price of those stocks drops, =
you get hit with a <strong>margin call</strong>, and need to put up more ca=
sh, or sell the stock. Margin calls can be a killer, forcing traders to unw=
ind at exactly the wrong time and lose a ton of money.</p><p style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Robinhoo=
d knew that the people who traded on its platforms (I hesitate to call them=
 customers, because &#8220;if you&#8217;re not paying, you&#8217;re the pro=
duct&#8221;) might get hit with margin calls, or might wipe themselves out =
by trading options without fully understanding them, or do any number of th=
ings that could lead to huge losses. And they did. The most infamous and tr=
agic example occurred in June, when 20-year-old Alex Kearns <a href=3D"http=
s://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkU1uxCAMhU8z7IiAhEy6YNFNrxHx40nQJBCBaZrb15=
1ZFCFbyDx_8OwtwpLLZY5ckf2FGa8DTIKzboAIhbUKZY7ByFFNvR4-WDBDkJOeWKzzowDsNm4GS=
wN2NLdFbzHm9FIIoTRbTRjcBG4chfXgvR76cVIPGPwodNC98G-ubSFC8mDgG8qVE7DNrIhHvfWf=
N_VF-zzPzifnO593OiqhBCUxUpAThSu3tHAsNkDh1Kxyd_Haoo8BuH3QZziuMT0j3VqBF-ufEHg=
7uIsL33KtpMiJl-xiWnMO3Yr7xqIhkCSWlL2m1clud8fPAWU4en8bxL6orjZXkfr9PY0VkzK6XI=
hD5edqd9heBfJnpry3FPGaIVm3QXhbh-8JvMycF0hQaDJhtki-SyWn-11rpfXbKvK2V2Lq72JgR=
A6ZVOkf-gv0bqBI" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">comm=
itted suicide</a> after mistakenly thinking he owed over $730k due to margi=
n trading.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">But Robinhood, and I hope you&#8217;ll pardon =
my French here, did. not. give. a. fuck.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1=
a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Until now, Robin=
hood has been able to push all of the risk it facilitates onto its users an=
d to the market at large, and hide behind language about market democratiza=
tion.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The markets, it turns out, do not give a fuck=
 either. Numbers are numbers. Words are just words.</p><p style=3D"color: #=
1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The delicio=
us irony of last week is that by encouraging so many of its customers to ma=
ke risky trades on margin, <strong>Robinhood Robinhooded Robinhood</strong>=
=2E It took on too much risk itself, got=
 hit with a margin call of its own, a=
nd was forced to reveal whose side it was really on - its own. Them&#8217;s=
 the breaks.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">This was bound to happen, and it will happen=
 again. Every move that Robinhood makes seems to increase entropy in the sy=
stem by encouraging riskier and riskier behavior by retail traders. While i=
t would have been impossible to predict exactly how this would go down, it =
was very easy to predict that something like it would. That&#8217;s the nat=
ure of chaos.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Today, we&#8217;ll cover:&nbsp;</p><ul styl=
e=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-specia=
l-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>We&#8217;re All Idiots. </strong>Me included.An=
d options trading is really hard.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px=
 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>How Robinhood Makes =
Money. </strong>Looking at Robinhood&#8217;s incentives.</p></li><li style=
=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Ro=
binhood, WSB, and Entropy. </strong>A look at Robinhood&#8217;s history and=
 chaos.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-speci=
al-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Robinhood Robinhooded Robinhood. </strong>What=
 happened last week?&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5=
px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Where Do We Go From Here? </stron=
g>Will Robinhood end up like Uber or Napster?&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
>Please don&#8217;t get me wrong here: I firmly believe that people should =
be allowed to manage their own money. That genie is out of the bottle, than=
ks in large part to Robinhood, and that&#8217;s a good thing overall. It&#8=
217;s just that, if you&#8217;re going to facilitate and profit from chaos,=
 don&#8217;t be surprised when that chaos turns back on you.</p><h3 style=
=3D"-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialias=
