MacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Col=
or Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-we=
ight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;"><strong>We&#8217=
;re All Idiots</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Let me start out with a personal story=
 that colors my views on all of this.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">I started my career at Ba=
nk of America Merrill Lynch in 2009. When you work at a financial instituti=
on, they put all sorts of restrictions on your ability to trade: you need t=
o get approval to buy stock or options on a specific company, you have to h=
old for thirty days, etc&#8230;&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The intention of the rule=
s is to protect the bank. Banks don&#8217;t want their employees trading on=
 insider information, of which there is necessarily plentiful amounts float=
ing around. But those rules also protected me.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: =
#1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">When I qui=
t in the summer of 2013, I owned a portfolio of stocks that I wanted to own=
 for a long time. Facebook at $19, Tesla at $29, Apple at a split-adjusted =
$15. I even owned 38 Bitcoin at ~$100 because they weren&#8217;t subject to=
 the bank&#8217;s restrictions. The list goes on, but I&#8217;m getting nau=
seous just writing it out.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Quitting meant no more restric=
tions. Time to make the <em>real</em> money. I logged into my Merrill Edge =
account and applied for access to options trading. I checked all the boxes =
-- good salary, professional experience with options, Series 7 and 63 licen=
sed, recently employed by Merrill itself -- and there was still a bunch of =
friction, but I finally got approved to trade options.</p><p style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Want to =
guess how the story ends?&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">I got my ass handed to me. I ma=
de all of the rookie mistakes, like buying short-dated Apple calls into ear=
nings, as if I had an insight that the millions of traders who watch Apple =
every day missed. Apple beat earnings - woohoo! - and my calls went to zero=
=2E My premium got wiped out by the vol=20=
crush. I wasn&#8217;t trading; I was =
gambling. Thankfully, I wasn&#8217;t trading on margin, or things could hav=
e gotten out of hand quickly.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">I tell you all of this for =
a couple reasons:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin=
: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1=
a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>No Judgment.=
</strong> I don&#8217;t look down on &#8220;Robinhood Traders.&#8221; I&#82=
17;ve been there.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px;=
 mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Options Are Hard.</strong> I was rel=
atively sophisticated on paper and still got crushed.&nbsp;</p></li><li sty=
le=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong=
>I Know How This Story Ends. </strong>Trading naked calls when they&#8217;r=
e going up is the most fun thing in the world; when they&#8217;re going dow=
n, it&#8217;s the least fun thing in the world. And Robinhood is in the fun=
 business.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">My views on Robinhood are not colore=
d by some patronizing opinion that other people -- retail traders, Redditor=
s, the WSB crew, whoever -- are some special class of idiot not capable of =
options trading. We are <strong>ALL</strong> idiots.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Even=
 the hedge funds who trade options don&#8217;t do it based on the opinions =
of some special class of genius. They do it based on systems that allow the=
m to predictably hedge risk, hence the &#8220;hedge.&#8221;&nbsp;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0=
;">If you&#8217;ve heard about Gamma Squeeze for the first time this week, =
for example, it&#8217;s made possible <em>because</em> hedge funds hedge. H=
ere&#8217;s what it means:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=
=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">If someone=
 is buying a call option, someone else is selling it. That person theoretic=
ally has uncapped downside risk, since a stock can theoretically go to infi=
nity dollars.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso=
-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0;">To hedge that risk, institutional investors who =
sell call options also buy the underlying stock to offset the risk based on=
 something called &#8220;<strong>Delta</strong>,&#8221; which describes how=
 sensitive an option is to a change in the price of the underlying stock.&n=
bsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format=
: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0;">If the Delta is .20, the price of the call is expected to move =
$0.20 for every $1 move in the underlying stock, so the option seller would=
 need to buy 20 shares to hedge the risk on the contract (options contracts=
 are 100 shares).&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px;=
 mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">With me? Ok. Well as the price of the underl=
ying stock changes, so does the Delta. The rate of change of the Delta is c=
alled the <strong>Gamma</strong>. Roughly, Delta measures speed, Gamma meas=
ures acceleration.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-=
special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0;">All else equal, Gamma increases the closer the pr=
ice of the stock is to the strike price of the call option, which means tha=
t as you get closer to the strike, Delta increases more quickly and the cal=
l seller needs to buy more underlying, faster, to stay hedged.&nbsp;</p></l=
i><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"=
>That drives the price up faster, too, as more people buy the stock, which =
means call sellers need to buy even more underlying to remain hedged, and s=
o on. That&#8217;s the Gamma Squeeze.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color:=
 #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Still wit=
h me? That&#8217;s just one thing that happens with options, and probably t=
he sexiest because acceleration is sexy and it works with you if you own th=
e call. But to really understand options, we need to understand more <stron=
g>Greeks</strong>, too.&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"=
margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Theta<=
/strong> deals with time - how the price of the option moves as it gets clo=
ser to expiration.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-=
special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Vega </strong>deals with volatility - the=
 more implied volatility, the more expensive the option. Vega explains the =
&#8220;vol crush&#8221; that wiped me out when I traded Apple calls.&nbsp;<=
/p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bul=
let;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0;"><strong>Rho</strong> deals with interest rates - options prices are =
sensitive to interest rates, too!</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">I&#8217;ll stop, bu=
t I hope my point is clear: <strong>this shit is complex</strong>.&nbsp;</p=
><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
